INSERT INTO `threats` VALUES (33,'0ef8feed-a3d8-46ac-8532-01a279e2b909','raptor threat','2025-08-16 16:28:45','test_final.puml','test_final.docx','The **C2 (Container) diagram** from the provided PlantUML sequence illustrates the high-level architecture of a simple login and file upload system with interactions between components. Here\'s a brief description of the architecture:\n\n1. **Actors:**\n   - The main external actor is the **User**, who interacts directly with the web application.\n\n2. **Key Components:**\n   - **WebApp (Web Application):** This is the core component of the system, responsible for handling user interactions such as login, file uploads (product specification and UML files), and displaying the generated threat report.\n   - **Database:** A storage component that validates user login credentials during the authentication process.\n   - **ThreatEngine:** A processing component responsible for analyzing the uploaded product specification and UML files to generate potential security threats.\n\n3. **Workflow:**\n   - The User initiates a **Login Request** to the WebApp, which forwards the credentials to the Database for validation. Based on the authentication result, the user receives success or failure feedback.\n   - After successful login, the User uploads **Product Specification** and **UML files** to the WebApp.\n   - The WebApp processes the uploaded files by communicating with the **ThreatEngine**, which analyzes the files and returns a **Threat Report**.\n   - Finally, the WebApp displays the **Threats Report** to the User.\n\n4. **Storage:**\n   - The uploaded files are securely handled, with the assumption (from the specifications) that all files will be stored in an **uploads/** directory.\n\nIn summary, the architecture exhibits a simple, modular design with clear separation between:\n- The **interface layer** (WebApp),\n- The **data layer** (Database and uploaded files),\n- And the **processing/logic layer** (ThreatEngine).To infer the system scope and trust boundaries from the provided **c1 (Component Model) diagram**, let’s analyze the system components and interactions described in your PlantUML diagram.\n\n---\n\n### **System Scope**:\nThe **system scope** includes all the components and interactions required to support the login, file upload, and threat generation features, as described in the product specification.\n\n#### System Components:\n1. **User**: The primary actor who interacts with the system to perform login, upload files, and view detected threats.\n2. **WebApp**: The application\'s core interface, handling login, file uploads, and communication with backend components like the database and ThreatEngine.\n3. **Database**: A secure data store used to validate login credentials and potentially store user data.\n4. **ThreatEngine**: A processing unit that analyzes the uploaded files for potential security threats and produces threat reports.\n5. **Uploads Directory**: A secure storage location for product specification and UML design files.\n\n---\n\n### **Trust Boundaries**:\nA **trust boundary** separates areas of the system that have different trust levels. It is crucial for identifying security concerns, such as where sanitization, validation, or encryption is needed during data exchanges.\n\n1. **User to WebApp Trust Boundary**:\n   - **Nature**: User interacts via the web application over the internet.\n   - **Risks**: Data in this boundary is untrusted (e.g., login credentials, file uploads). Potential threats here include input validation vulnerabilities, malicious files, and unauthorized access.\n   - **Mitigation**:\n     - Use HTTPS to encrypt communication.\n     - Implement authentication mechanisms like hashing passwords.\n     - Validate all inputs and files uploaded by the user.\n\n2. **WebApp to Database Trust Boundary**:\n   - **Nature**: The WebApp queries the database to validate credentials or potentially store user-related data.\n   - **Risks**: This involves trusted data sources, but if injection attacks (like SQL injection) occur, the integrity and confidentiality of the database could be compromised.\n   - **Mitigation**:\n     - Use parameterized queries and ORM frameworks to prevent SQL injection.\n     - Restrict database user privileges.\n     - Ensure the database connection is secure.\n\n3. **WebApp to ThreatEngine Trust Boundary**:\n   - **Nature**: The WebApp submits uploaded files to the ThreatEngine for analysis, and the ThreatEngine generates threat reports.\n   - **Risks**: The ThreatEngine needs to handle potentially malicious or malformed files with care, as they may affect its accurate threat detection or cause system compromises.\n   - **Mitigation**:\n     - Use secure file transfer protocols between the WebApp and ThreatEngine.\n     - Validate file types, formats, and sizes before processing.\n     - Sandbox the ThreatEngine to isolate it from critical system components.\n\n4. **ThreatEngine to WebApp Boundary**:\n   - **Nature**: The ThreatEngine sends threat analysis reports back to the WebApp for display to the end-user.\n   - **Risks**: Inaccurate or forged reports could lead to misinformation or misidentification of threats.\n   - **Mitigation**:\n     - Ensure integrity and authenticity of reports (e.g., using digital signatures).\n     - Implement logic to validate the output and prevent harmful or unformatted data from reaching the user.\n\n5. **WebApp to Uploads Directory Trust Boundary**:\n   - **Nature**: Files uploaded by the User are stored securely in the `uploads/` directory.\n   - **Risks**: Potential risks include directory traversal attacks, unauthorized access to uploaded files, and malware execution.\n   - **Mitigation**:\n     - Use access controls to restrict direct access to the `uploads/` directory.\n     - Store files with unique, unpredictable filenames to prevent overwriting or unauthorized downloads.\n     - Regularly scan the directory for malware.\n\n---\n\n### **Summary**:\n- The **system scope** is defined as a login and file processing system with secure, trusted interactions between all system components, and careful inspection of all incoming data from untrusted users.\n- The **trust boundaries** focus heavily on:\n  - User input (login, file uploads).\n  - Safe storage and processing of files (uploads directory, ThreatEngine).\n  - Database communication for authentication.\n  - Output integrity (threat reports).\n\nEnsuring strong trust boundaries will enhance the security and reliability of the system.Here is a list of critical assets for the described system:\n\n### 1. **User Data**\n   - **User credentials** (username, password) stored securely in the database.\n   - **Session information** for authenticated users.\n\n### 2. **Uploaded Files**\n   - **Product specification files** stored in the `uploads/` directory.\n   - **UML design files** stored in the same `uploads/` directory.\n\n### 3. **Threat Reports**\n   - Output generated by the **ThreatEngine**, including detailed information about possible security threats identified from the uploaded files.\n\n### 4. **Authentication System**\n   - The **login mechanism** ensuring secure access control.\n   - **Password protection** and hashing mechanisms used for storing credentials.\n\n### 5. **ThreatEngine**\n   - The **algorithm** or module responsible for threat analysis, which generates security-related insights from the uploaded files.\n\n### 6. **Admin Reports**\n   - The **aggregate reports** that Admin views summarizing identified security threats.\n\n### 7. **Database**\n   - Stores user account information (e.g., username, hashed password) and potentially other session-related data.\n\n### 8. **Web Application**\n   - The **front-end and back-end** logic that facilitates file uploads, user interactions, and threat analysis.\n\n### 9. **Uploads/ Directory**\n   - Secure storage for all uploaded files.\n   - Ensuring proper read/write privileges for the directory while preventing unauthorized access.\n\n### 10. **Concurrent User Support**\n   - Ensuring secure handling of up to **100 concurrent user sessions** without data leakage or service interruptions.\n\n### 11. **System Logs**\n   - Logs for **login attempts**, **file uploads**, **threat analysis results**, and **admin activity** for monitoring and troubleshooting.\n\nThese assets are critical to the system\'s functionality, security, and user experience, and should be protected with appropriate measures to ensure confidentiality, integrity, and availability.1. **Confidentiality**: Ensure unauthorized users cannot access sensitive files or threat reports.  \n2. **Integrity**: Protect uploaded files and threat reports from unauthorized modification.  \n3. **Availability**: Maintain consistent access to the system for up to 100 concurrent users.  \n4. **Authentication and Authorization**: Verify user identity and enforce access control to system features.  \n5. **Auditability**: Log all user activities, file uploads, and threat generation processes for traceability.  ','[{\"scenario\": \"Malicious user uses brute force attack to gain unauthorized access so that they can compromise user accounts.\", \"severity\": \"High\", \"countermeasure\": \"Implement account lockout mechanism and use CAPTCHA after multiple failed login attempts.\"}, {\"scenario\": \"Attacker uses file upload vulnerabilities to upload malicious files so that they can infect the system.\", \"severity\": \"Critical\", \"countermeasure\": \"Validate file types and scan files for malware before saving them to the uploads directory.\"}, {\"scenario\": \"Threat actor uses network sniffing to intercept login credentials so that they can impersonate legitimate users.\", \"severity\": \"High\", \"countermeasure\": \"Enforce HTTPS and TLS for secure data transmission during login.\"}, {\"scenario\": \"Malicious user uses broken access controls to view administrative reports so that they can exploit sensitive threat data.\", \"severity\": \"Critical\", \"countermeasure\": \"Implement role-based access controls and authenticate all API access points for administrative functionalities.\"}, {\"scenario\": \"Attacker uses SQL injection to compromise database integrity so that they can access sensitive user information.\", \"severity\": \"Critical\", \"countermeasure\": \"Use parameterized queries and sanitize all user inputs to prevent SQL injection attacks.\"}, {\"scenario\": \"Insider uses their access to upload files exceeding allowed limits so that they can cause disk space exhaustion.\", \"severity\": \"Medium\", \"countermeasure\": \"Set file size limits for uploads and monitor disk usage regularly to prevent exhaustion.\"}, {\"scenario\": \"Threat actor uses credential stuffing to log in using leaked passwords so that they can impersonate legitimate users.\", \"severity\": \"High\", \"countermeasure\": \"Enable multi-factor authentication to prevent unauthorized access through stolen credentials.\"}, {\"scenario\": \"Malicious user uses directory traversal attack to access unauthorized files so that they can exploit sensitive data.\", \"severity\": \"Critical\", \"countermeasure\": \"Restrict file path inputs and apply strong input validation to prevent directory traversal.\"}]','https://www.plantuml.com/plantuml/png/TP2nRW8n38RtF8LV07LdGA1UORbA5TU3sIHMBrAQ1DiP-lOaEa6lQhjuy6Vz_oTlHP6rV0Q3LXF3ACIc3LXju4oNNSvhwDE7Zt2aQo5HCsyRxr3nWa9hE67m3fNWcSbHL8z1p1t3Qf6rAphLA2dXEwdYLdal6egr9FAqHnyAa_dbC-QGqC4R9rUimf39_dSpllQmzu4MrkyJ4-fBh5NL_42Hk9dFQp5B_CDy1jKz9_x3lVEI0tuzShOKNVlh3G00');
